## Phase 0 – First 30–90 Days – Mindset, Setup & Strong Start (Very Important)

### 1. Life-Changing Mindset (Read This Every Morning)
- You are not late — first year is the best time to start  
- Small daily improvement = huge results in 3–4 years  
- Compare only with your past self — not Instagram toppers  
- College CGPA matters (aim 7.5+ — below 7.0 hurts many companies)  
- Mistakes are teachers — make them fast and learn  
- Balance is power: code + college + health + friends + family  
- No zero days — even 30 min is progress  
- Your future job = 70% self-learning + 20% projects + 10% college  

### 2. Setup Everything (Do in First Week)
- Laptop: VS Code + Python + Chrome + Git  
- Accounts: GitHub (clean username), LinkedIn, LeetCode, CodeChef, Kaggle  
- Tracking: one Google Sheet or Notion  
  - Week number  
  - DSA problems solved  
  - Project progress  
  - Hours coded  
  - One win  
  - Energy (1–10)  

### 3. Daily Routine Options (Choose One – Stick 80% Days)
Option A – Busy with college (1–2 hours)  
- 40 min coding / DSA  
- 30 min video / theory  
- 20 min revision or project  

Option B – Medium free time (2.5–4 hours)  
- 1 hour DSA  
- 1 hour project / ML  
- 45 min theory / video  
- 30 min LinkedIn / application  

Option C – High motivation (4.5–6 hours)  
- 1.5–2 hours DSA  
- 1.5 hours project  
- 1 hour ML/DL learning  
- 30 min outreach  

Sunday Ritual (1–2 hours)  
- Review week  
- Re-solve 5–10 problems  
- Update trackers  
- Plan next week  

### 4. Health & Balance – Never Ignore
- Sleep 7–8 hours  
- Walk / exercise 30 min daily  
- Drink water  
- One easy day/week (revision only)  
- Eat normal food  
- Talk to family/friends — don’t become robot  

Phase 1 – Absolute Beginner (Months 1–6 First Year)

1. Learn Python (Most Important)  
Step-by-Step (Do in Order)  
1. Install Python 3 + VS Code (1 day)  
2. Hello World, print, input  
3. Variables, data types (int, float, str, bool)  
4. Operators (+ - * / % == > <)  
5. If-else, elif, nested if  
6. Loops: for, while, break, continue  
7. Lists: add, remove, slice, loop  
8. Tuples, dictionaries, sets  
9. Functions: def, return, arguments  
10. Strings: split, join, replace, find  
11. File handling: read/write txt  
12. Basic OOP: class, object, __init__  
13. Modules: import math, random  
14. Exception: try-except  
15. List/dict comprehension  

Resources (Free & Easy)  
- CodeWithHarry Python (Hindi – best for Indian students)  
- Apna College Python playlist  
- freeCodeCamp Python (English)  
- W3Schools Python  

Goal: Write 50–100 small programs without copy (calculator, guessing game, pattern print)

2. Easy DSA in Python  
Platforms  
- CodeChef Starters  
- LeetCode easy  
- GeeksforGeeks beginner  

Topics (First 6 Months)  
- Pattern printing (stars, numbers)  
- Basic math (prime, factorial, palindrome number)  
- Arrays/lists (sum, max, min, reverse, rotate)  
- Strings (reverse, palindrome, count vowels)  
- Simple searching (linear)  
- Simple sorting (bubble intro)  

Target: 150–300 easy problems  
Do 4–7 per week — think first, don’t copy

3. First Projects (Python)  
Do 5–8 small projects  
1. Number Guessing Game  
2. To-Do List (save to file)  
3. Quiz Game (MCQ)  
4. Student Marks Manager  
5. Simple Calculator with menu  
6. Password Generator  
7. Rock Paper Scissors  
8. Currency Converter (hardcode rates)  

Rule: Finish one every 3–5 weeks. Put on GitHub with README.

4. First Computer Basics  
- What is RAM, CPU, storage  
- Binary basics  
- Compiler vs interpreter  
- What is Git & GitHub  

Resources  
- Apna College Computer Fundamentals  
- Neso Academy YouTube  

